The decision is a victory for Chelsea boss Jose Mourinho, who has complained of a campaign against the Premier League leaders ever since striker Diego Costa was hit with a three-match retrospective ban for a stamp on Liverpool’s Emre Can.

The FA also looked into suggestions that Ivanovic had bitten McCarthy on the shoulder during the incident, a claim the Serb vehemently denies. But after discussions with Everton on Thursday, the FA decided there were no grounds to take that allegation further.

But both clubs have been charged with failing to control their players after the clash that marred Chelsea’s 1-0 win. And despite the escape for Ivanovic, Chelsea are believed to be unhappy at being charged at all.

Everton boss Roberto Martinez said Ivanovic should have been sent off but the FA have chosen to take a lenient approach, as they did when Leicester boss Nigel Pearson went unpunished for putting his hands round the neck of Crystal Palace’s James McArthur last Saturday. 

